Rating: 2
Good as it may be, it is a rather rudimentary preparation--a very obvious one. You might use it to overcome the tastelessness of a nation-wide chain pre-cut cut. Salt, as somebody has remarked is unnecessary. If you crave for more, salt it when cooked and then with freshly ground cristal sea salt with its superb whiff of iodine. Soy sauce... Most are mediocre or anodine (most but not all). It works better with pork and vegetable and improves with a few drops of sherry vinegar and/ot bourbon (etc.). Far preferable is the Chinese oyster sauce preferably from a Chinese store. While I may not be ready to reproduce the recipe as such, I would relish to have it served in a restarant or... your home. I'd bring a Shiraz from down-under, or a decent Zinfandel, and let's not forget there's always a Bordeaux for any imaginable life/death situation. Basta, tripo[d][t]

